ww.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_esc_aux_sc.htm |title=Auxiliary Sub Chasers of WWII, Converted Merchant Ships, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 March 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Empire Geraint||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was [[torpedo]]ed and damaged at [[Milford Haven]], [[Pembrokeshire]] by {{GS|U-775||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was beached with her back broken. Refloated on 30 April, repaired and returned to service.<ref name=Ships>{{cite book | first = and Sawyer, L A| last = Mitchell, W H | year = 1995| month = | title = The Empire Ships| page = not cited | publisher = Lloyd's of London Press Ltd| location = London, New York, Hamburg, Hong Kong|isbn=1-85044-275-4 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Green Hill Park||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Canada|1921}}\n|desc=The [[Park ship]] was damaged by fire at [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. She was declared a [[constructive total loss]] but was repaired and re-entered service in 1946 as the Panamanian-flagged ''Phaeax II''.<ref name=ParkAM>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/ParkA.html |title=Park Ships A-M |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Hansa|1928|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[ocean liner]] struck a mine and sank in the Baltic Sea off the ''[[Gedser Lightship]]'' ({{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}) off [[Warnem\u00fcnde]], [[Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania]]. The whole crew was saved. She was salvaged c. 1949 and returned to service by the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=seekrieg194503/><ref name=Kap22/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Albert_Ballin |title=SS Albert Ballin |publisher=en.wikipedia.org |accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German guard ship|IV 53 Scarpanto||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The guard ship was sunk by three [[Royal Navy]] ships off the Istrian coast. Raised, repaired, and put in Yugoslav service as ''Pag'' in 1952.<ref name=\"Guard Ships of WWII, Germany\">{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_conc_patrol.htm |title=Guard Ships of WWII, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5268657|shipname=Pag |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCT 492}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[landing craft tank]] Mk 3 capsized and sank in the [[Red Sea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/uk/brit_aws_lct3.htm |title=LCT 3) Landing Craft, Royal Navy |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Navalhistory.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW2BritishLossesbyDate3.htm |title=Royal Navy vessels lost at sea Jan. '44-Nov. 45 |publisher=Navalhistory.net |accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|Japanese auxiliary tanker|Rikko Maru||2}} \n|flag={{army|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary tanker broke in two at the location of a torpedo hit inflicted on 31 August 1944 and sank off [[Kirun]], [[Formosa]] ({{coord|25|09|N|121|44|E}}) during a [[typhoon]] while awaiting repairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Rikko_t.htm |title=Japanese Oilers|publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Robert Mohring|1923|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[hospital ship]] was bombed and sunk in a RAF Bomber Command air raid on [[Sa\u00dfnitz]], Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania with the loss of 353 lives.<ref name=seekrieg194503/><ref>{{csr |register=MSI |id=5606645 |shipname=Robert Mohring |accessdate=27 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kriegstote.org/cgi-bin