dfleet.com/RO-41_t.htm|title=Japanese Submarines |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Robert Muller VII||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk by a mine in the Skagerrak off [[Nidingen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?174405 |title=Robert Muller VII (+1945) |date= |publisher=Wreck Site |accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rotenfels||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk off the Norwegian coast by de Havilland Mosquito aircraft of 143, 235 and 248 Squadrons, Royal Air Force.<ref name=seekrieg194503/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-1003||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC/41]] [[submarine]] attempted to ram {{HMCS|New Glasgow|K320|6}} ({{navy|Canada|1911}}) in the Atlantic Ocean but was severely damaged in the process. She was scuttled three days later ({{coord|55|25|N|6|53|W}}) with the loss of seventeen of her 48 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMCS|Thetford Mines|K459|6}} ({{navy|Canada|1911}}).<ref name=U1003>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u1003.htm |title=U-1003 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Utviken||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and sank in the [[Kattegat]] off [[Sj\u00e6llands Odde]], Denmark.<ref name=HomeU>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsu.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet - WW II, Ships starting with U |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=11 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 2022 Emil Colsmann||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Kattegat]] by {{ship|Soviet submarine|L-21||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union|1935}}).<ref name=s