{"title_page": "BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a", "text_new": "{{Infobox volleyball club\n| clubname    = BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a\n| short name  = BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a\n| nickname    = \n| image       = BBTSBielskoBiala_Logo.png\n| fullname    = Bielsko-Bialskie Towarzystwo Sportowe Sp\u00f3\u0142ka Akcyjna \n| founded     = 1999\n| dissolved   = \n| ground      = [[D\u0119bowiec Sports Arena]]<br />ul. Karbowa 26<br />43-300 [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]]\n| capacity    = 3,009\n| chairman    = {{flagicon|POL}} Miros\u0142aw Krysta\n| manager     = {{flagicon|NED}} [[Arie Cornelis Brokking]]\n| captain     = \n| league      = 1st Polish Volleyball League\n| season      = \n| position    = \n| website     = http://bbtsbielsko.pl/\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_s1  = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_s2  =\n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| current     =\n}}\n\n'''BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a SA''' is a [[Poland|Polish]] professional [[volleyball]] team based in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]], founded in 1999. From 2013 to 2018 the club played in the highest level of [[Polish Volleyball League]]<ref>[http://www.pzps.pl/PLPS-podjela-decyzje-o-powiekszeniu-PlusLigi.html ''PLPS podj\u0119\u0142a decyzj\u0119 o powi\u0119kszeniu PlusLigi''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205071822/http://www.pzps.pl/PLPS-podjela-decyzje-o-powiekszeniu-PlusLigi.html |date=2014-12-05 }} \u2013 pzps.pl \u2013 18-06-2013</ref>. Since 2018 club has been playing in 1st Polish Volleyball League.\n\n==Achievements==\n* [[PlusLiga|Polish Championship]]\n*: [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 1993\n* [[Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]]\n*: [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 1994\n\n==Coaches==\n{|\n|-\n| '''2012\u20132014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Janusz Bu\u0142kowski\n|- \n| '''2014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Wiktor Krebok\n|-\n| '''2014\u20132015''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Piotr Gruszka]]\n|-\n| '''2015\u20132016''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Krzysztof Stelmach]]\n|-\n| '''2016''' || {{flagicon|SVK}} Miroslav Palgut\n|-\n| '''2016\u20132017''' || {{flagicon|SVK}} Rastislav Chud\u00edk\n|-\n| '''2017\u20132019''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Pawe\u0142 Gradowski\n|-\n| '''2019\u2013present''' || {{flagicon|NED}} [[Harry Brokking]]\n|}\n\n==Team==\n{{main|BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a squads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Volleyball in Poland]]\n* [[Sports in Poland]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:BPTS Siatkarz Bielsko-Biala}}\n[[Category:Polish volleyball clubs]]\n[[Category:Sport in Silesian Voivodeship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox volleyball club\n| clubname    = BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a\n| short name  = BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a\n| nickname    = \n| image       = BBTSBielskoBiala_Logo.png\n| fullname    = Bielsko-Bialskie Towarzystwo Sportowe Sp\u00f3\u0142ka Akcyjna \n| founded     = 1999\n| dissolved   = \n| ground      = [[D\u0119bowiec Sports Arena]]<br />ul. Karbowa 26<br />43-300 [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]]\n| capacity    = 3,009\n| chairman    = {{flagicon|POL}} Miros\u0142aw Krysta\n| manager     = {{flagicon|NED}} [[Harry Brokking]]\n| captain     = \n| league      = 1st Polish Volleyball League\n| season      = \n| position    = \n| website     = http://bbtsbielsko.pl/\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_s1  = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_s2  =\n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| current     =\n}}\n\n'''BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a SA''' is a [[Poland|Polish]] professional [[volleyball]] team based in [[Bielsko-Bia\u0142a]], founded in 1999. From 2013 to 2018 the club played in the highest level of [[Polish Volleyball League]]<ref>[http://www.pzps.pl/PLPS-podjela-decyzje-o-powiekszeniu-PlusLigi.html ''PLPS podj\u0119\u0142a decyzj\u0119 o powi\u0119kszeniu PlusLigi''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205071822/http://www.pzps.pl/PLPS-podjela-decyzje-o-powiekszeniu-PlusLigi.html |date=2014-12-05 }} \u2013 pzps.pl \u2013 18-06-2013</ref>. Since 2018 club has been playing in 1st Polish Volleyball League.\n\n==Achievements==\n* [[PlusLiga|Polish Championship]]\n*: [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 1993\n* [[Polish Cup of men's volleyball|Polish Cup]]\n*: [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] '''(x1)''' 1994\n\n==Coaches==\n{|\n|-\n| '''2012\u20132014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Janusz Bu\u0142kowski\n|- \n| '''2014''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Wiktor Krebok\n|-\n| '''2014\u20132015''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Piotr Gruszka]]\n|-\n| '''2015\u20132016''' || {{flagicon|POL}} [[Krzysztof Stelmach]]\n|-\n| '''2016''' || {{flagicon|SVK}} Miroslav Palgut\n|-\n| '''2016\u20132017''' || {{flagicon|SVK}} Rastislav Chud\u00edk\n|-\n| '''2017\u20132019''' || {{flagicon|POL}} Pawe\u0142 Gradowski\n|-\n| '''2019\u2013present''' || {{flagicon|NED}} [[Harry Brokking]]\n|}\n\n==Team==\n{{main|BBTS Bielsko-Bia\u0142a squads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Volleyball in Poland]]\n* [[Sports in Poland]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:BPTS Siatkarz Bielsko-Biala}}\n[[Category:Polish volleyball clubs]]\n[[Category:Sport in Silesian Voivodeship]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBTS_Bielsko-Bia%C5%82a"}
{"title_page": "Too High to Die", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Too High to Die\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Meat Puppets]]\n| cover      = Meat Puppets Too High to Die.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 25, 1994\n| recorded   = 1993\n| venue      =\n| studio     = The Warehouse, [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Alternative rock]]\n*[[grunge]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Francis |first1=Claire |title=20 Years On: Meat Puppets \u2013 \u2018Too High To Die\u2019 |url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/20-years-on-meat-puppets-too-high-to-die/ |website=Tone Deaf |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=52|s=06}}\n| label      = [[London Records|London]]\n| producer   = Meat Puppets, [[Paul Leary]]\n| prev_title = [[Forbidden Places]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[No Joke!]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n}}\n\n'''''Too High to Die''''' is the eighth studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band the [[Meat Puppets]]. The album was released on January 25, 1994, by [[London Records]]. It was produced by [[Butthole Surfers]] guitarist [[Paul Leary]]. The album's title is a parody of [[Ramones|The Ramones]]' 1984 album ''[[Too Tough to Die]]''.\n\nA limited edition of ''Too High to Die'' included the 10\" vinyl promo [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Raw Meat (EP)|Raw Meat]]''. The cover art on this limited edition features more color than the simply pink-toned normal cover.\n\nThe album was supported by a lengthy tour, which included spots opening for the likes of [[Blind Melon]], [[Soul Asylum]], and [[Stone Temple Pilots]] (and shortly before the album's release, [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]).\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/too-high-to-die-mw0000107415|title=Too High to Die - Meat Puppets Review|author=Prato, Greg|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=2017-10-22}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev3score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=RA1-PA2006|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|date=2011-05-27|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|page=2006|isbn=9780857125958|language=en}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev4score = B\u2013<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ew.com/article/1994/02/18/too-high-die/|title=Too High to Die|date=1994-02-18|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=2017-10-22|author=Eddy, Chuck|authorlink=Chuck Eddy|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating-Christgau|hm1}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVQbszFuEGMC|title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=2000-10-15|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishing]]|page=202|chapter=Meat Puppets: Too High to Die|chapter-url=http://robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=2338|isbn=9780312245603|language=en}}</ref> \n|rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n|rev5score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-02-06/entertainment/ca-19543_1_meat-puppets |title=In Brief |last=Hochman |first=Steve |date=1994-02-06 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=2018-05-11 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/meatpuppets/albums/album/99987/review/5942113/too_high_to_die|title=Too High to Die Review|last=Weisel|first=Al|authorlink=Al Weisel|date=1994-06-02|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001015423/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/meatpuppets/albums/album/99987/review/5942113/too_high_to_die|archive-date=2007-10-01|url-status=|access-date=2017-10-22}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]'' \n|rev7score = 8/10<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-bfuAAAAMAAJ |title=Spin Alternative Record Guide |last=Weisbard |first=Eric |last2=Marks |first2=Craig |date=1995 |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |isbn=9780679755746 |language=en |author-link=Eric Weisbard}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Too High to Die'' sold very well due to the success of its single \"Backwater\", which reached #2 and #11 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock Tracks]] and [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] charts respectively. The album itself also reached #1 on the Heatseekers chart, making it one of the Meat Puppets' most successful and highest ranking albums to date. The album was certified gold by the [[RIAA]] on October 6, 1994.\n\nThe rarely-seen video for \"We Don't Exist\" was nominated for \"Best Metal/Hard Rock Video\" at the [[1995 MTV Video Music Awards]], but lost to [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie's]] \"[[More Human than Human]]\".\n\nIn May 2012, the title of a book about the Meat Puppets' history borrowed part of the album's title, ''Too High to Die: Meet the Meat Puppets''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amzn.com/1493752324 |title=Too High to Die: Meet the Meat Puppets: Greg Prato: 9781493752324: Amazon.com: Books |publisher=Amzn.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, ''[[Guitar World]]'' placed ''Too High to Die'' at number 44 in their \"Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994\" list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |title=Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994 |date=July 14, 2014 |work=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=July 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715053900/http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |archive-date=July 15, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, the Alternative Nation website listed ''Too High to Die'' at number 9 in their \"Top 10 Alternative Rock Albums Of 1994\" list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alternativenation.net/top-10-rock-albums-1994/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603044640/http://www.alternativenation.net/top-10-rock-albums-1994/ |archivedate=2015-06-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Curt Kirkwood]], unless otherwise noted.\n{{Track listing\n\n| title1 = Violet Eyes\n| length1 = 3:51\n\n| title2 = Never to Be Found\n| length2 = 4:46\n\n| title3 = [[We Don't Exist]]\n| length3 = 3:44\n\n| title4 = Severed Goddess Hand\n| length4 = 2:59\n\n| title5 = Flaming Heart\n| length5 = 4:49\n\n| title6 = Shine\n| length6 = 3:50\n\n| title7 = Station\n| writer7 = [[Cris Kirkwood]]\n| length7 = 2:22\n\n| title8 = [[Roof with a Hole]]\n| length8 = 3:34\n\n| title9 = [[Backwater (song)|Backwater]]\n| length9 = 3:42\n\n| title10 = Things\n| length10 = 4:06\n\n| title11 = Why?\n| length11 = 4:20\n\n| title12 = Evil Love\n| writer12 = Cris Kirkwood\n| length12 = 3:07\n\n| title13 = Comin' Down\n| note13 = features \"[[Lake of Fire (song)|Lake of Fire]]\" as a [[hidden track]]\n| length13 = 6:56\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Meat Puppets'''\n\n*[[Derrick Bostrom]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]], [[painting]]s\n*[[Cris Kirkwood]] \u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[vocals]], [[illustration]]s\n*[[Curt Kirkwood]] \u2013 [[guitar]], vocals, paintings\n\n'''Production'''\n\n*Greg Calbi \u2013 [[audio mastering|mastering]]\n*[[Dave Jerden]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*[[Paul Leary]] \u2013 [[record producer|producer]], mixing\n*Meat Puppets \u2013 producer\n*Stuart Sullivan \u2013 [[audio engineering|engineer]], mixing\n*Brad Vosburg \u2013 engineer\n*Josh Kiser \u2013 assistant\n*Michael Halsband \u2013 [[photography]]\n\n==Charts==\n'''Album''' \u2013 [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] (North America)\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1994)\n!Peak\nposition\n|-\n|[[Billboard Heatseekers|''Billboard'' Heatseekers]]\n|1\n|-\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]\n|62\n|}\n'''Singles''' \u2013 Billboard (North America)\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1994\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\"Backwater\"\n|[[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock Tracks]]\n|2\n|-\n|[[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]]\n|11\n|-\n|[[Billboard Hot 100|The Billboard Hot 100]]\n|47\n|-\n|[[Mainstream Top 40|Top 40 Mainstream]]\n|31\n|-\n|\"We Don't Exist\"\n|[[Mainstream Rock Tracks]]\n|28\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Meat Puppets}}\n\n[[Category:1994 albums]]\n[[Category:Meat Puppets albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Paul Leary]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Too High to Die\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Meat Puppets]]\n| cover      = Meat Puppets Too High to Die.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 25, 1994\n| recorded   = 1993\n| venue      =\n| studio     = The Warehouse, [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Alternative rock]]\n*[[grunge]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Francis |first1=Claire |title=20 Years On: Meat Puppets \u2013 \u2018Too High To Die\u2019 |url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/20-years-on-meat-puppets-too-high-to-die/ |website=Tone Deaf |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=52|s=06}}\n| label      = [[London Records|London]]\n| producer   = Meat Puppets, [[Paul Leary]]\n| prev_title = [[Forbidden Places]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[No Joke!]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n}}\n\n'''''Too High to Die''''' is the eighth studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band the [[Meat Puppets]]. The album was released on January 25, 1994, by [[London Records]]. It was produced by [[Butthole Surfers]] guitarist [[Paul Leary]]. The album's title is a parody of [[Ramones|The Ramones]]' 1984 album ''[[Too Tough to Die]]''.\n\nA limited edition of ''Too High to Die'' included the 10\" vinyl promo [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Raw Meat (EP)|Raw Meat]]''. The cover art on this limited edition features more color than the simply pink-toned normal cover.\n\nThe album was supported by a lengthy tour, which included spots opening for the likes of [[Blind Melon]], [[Soul Asylum]], and [[Stone Temple Pilots]] (and shortly before the album's release, [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]).\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/too-high-to-die-mw0000107415|title=Too High to Die - Meat Puppets Review|author=Prato, Greg|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=2017-10-22}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev3score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=RA1-PA2006|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|date=2011-05-27|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|page=2006|isbn=9780857125958|language=en}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev4score = B\u2013<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ew.com/article/1994/02/18/too-high-die/|title=Too High to Die|date=1994-02-18|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=2017-10-22|author=Eddy, Chuck|authorlink=Chuck Eddy|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating-Christgau|hm1}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVQbszFuEGMC|title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=2000-10-15|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishing]]|page=202|chapter=Meat Puppets: Too High to Die|chapter-url=http://robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=2338|isbn=9780312245603|language=en}}</ref> \n|rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n|rev5score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-02-06/entertainment/ca-19543_1_meat-puppets |title=In Brief |last=Hochman |first=Steve |date=1994-02-06 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=2018-05-11 |language=en-US |issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev6scor